However I think you may be on to something for the clock timing because I tried changing the SPI frequency from 133 MHz to either 100 MHz or 104 MHZ. I don't remember what I did.

I'm still getting magic bitmask failures but I did see strange results. Under certain conditions, it will read the bitmask correctly. I remember trying to boot from QSPI, the boot failed, I booted back from SD card with a changed max frequency in the device tree, and then it read correctly. However, when I erased the QSPI it went back to 0x99C5.

In some cases, it would read 0x19C5 instead of 0x1985.

So, I think it could be the SPI timing.

Just for reference, in the old working kernel version, the max frequency was set to 133 MHz. And this lines up with what's stated in their [datasheet](https://www.mxic.com.tw/Lists/Datasheet/Attachments/8959/MX66L2G45G,%203V,%202Gb,%20v1.1.pdf), particularly Page 28.

I'll keep lowering the frequency and let y'all know what I find.
